Auckland bicycle count and rainfall

Lovdip Singh

Under Modules | Data | Bikes on Canvas you have data on the number of people counted cycling in Auckland and the amount of rain.

Goal of study

To analyse Auckland bicycle count data as well as rainfall data in the Auckland region to determine how cycle counts change according to rainfall.

Cleaning data - total number of cyclists counted for each day, summary of the rainfall for each day

#Join all bike data
bike_files <- list.files("../data/BIKES/",pattern=".csv",full=TRUE)
bike_data <- map(bike_files,read_csv)
## 
##  Column specification 
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   Date = col_character()
## )
##  Use `spec()` for the full column specifications.
## 
## 
##  Column specification 
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   Date = col_character()
## )
##  Use `spec()` for the full column specifications.
## 
## 
##  Column specification 
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   Date = col_character()
## )
##  Use `spec()` for the full column specifications.
bike_tidy <- map(bike_data, pivot_longer, values_to ="rider_count", names_to ="counter",-Date)
allbikes <- bind_rows(bike_tidy) %>% 
  separate(Date, into=c('wday', 'day', 'month', 'year')) %>%
  group_by(wday, day, month, year) %>%
  summarise(total=sum(rider_count, na.rm = T))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'wday', 'day', 'month' (override with `.groups` argument)
#Join all rain data
rain_files <- list.files("../data/rain/",pattern=".txt",full=TRUE)
rain_data <- map(rain_files, read_csv, skip=9) %>% bind_rows(.)
##

rain_tidy <- rain_data %>%
  separate('Date(NZST)', into=c('year', 'month', 'day'), sep=c(4,6,8)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(Station))

#Month and days to char
months <- c('Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec')
month_chr <- sprintf("%02d", 1:12)
for (i in seq(along=months)){
  pos <- which(allbikes$month == months[i])
  allbikes$month[pos] <- month_chr[i]
}

days <- as.character(1:9)
days_chr <- sprintf("%02d", 1:9)
for (i in seq(along=days)){
  pos <- which(allbikes$day == days[i])
  allbikes$day[pos] <- days_chr[i]
}


#Average rain data per data across Auckland, using Mangere and Albany data
allrain <- rain_tidy %>%
  group_by(year, month, day) %>%
  summarise(mean_rain_mm=mean(`Amount(mm)`))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'year', 'month' (override with `.groups` argument)
#Add rain data 
final_tidy <- inner_join(allbikes, allrain, by=c('year', 'month', 'day')) %>%
  arrange(year, month, day)

#Insert season column with appropriate season
final_tidy$season=as.character(NA)
seasons <- rep(c('summer', 'autumn', 'winter', 'spring'), 4, length.out=13)
pos <- c(0,
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='19' & final_tidy$month=='03' & final_tidy$year=='2016')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='20' & final_tidy$month=='06' & final_tidy$year=='2016')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='22' & final_tidy$month=='09' & final_tidy$year=='2016')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='20' & final_tidy$month=='12' & final_tidy$year=='2016')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='19' & final_tidy$month=='03' & final_tidy$year=='2017')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='20' & final_tidy$month=='06' & final_tidy$year=='2017')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='22' & final_tidy$month=='09' & final_tidy$year=='2017')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='21' & final_tidy$month=='12' & final_tidy$year=='2017')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='20' & final_tidy$month=='03' & final_tidy$year=='2018')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='20' & final_tidy$month=='06' & final_tidy$year=='2018')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='22' & final_tidy$month=='09' & final_tidy$year=='2018')),
        max(which(final_tidy$day=='21' & final_tidy$month=='12' & final_tidy$year=='2018')),
        nrow(final_tidy))
x <- 1:13
for (elt in x){
  start <- pos[elt] + 1
  end <- pos[elt+1]
  final_tidy[start:end,7] <- seasons[elt]
}

#change date to lubridate format
final_tidy <- final_tidy %>%
  unite(date, day, month, year, sep='')
final_tidy$date <- dmy(final_tidy$date)

#Final touch ups
final_tidy$DayOfYear <- as.numeric(format(final_tidy$date, "%j"))
final_tidy$season <- factor(final_tidy$season, levels=c('autumn', 'winter', 'spring', 'summer'))
final_tidy$wday <- factor(final_tidy$wday, levels=c('Mon','Tue','Wed','Thu','Fri','Sat','Sun'))
final_tidy$year <- year(final_tidy$date)
final_tidy$year <- factor(final_tidy$year)
final_tidy

Graphs

(plot1 <- final_tidy %>% ggplot(aes(x=date, y=total, col=mean_rain_mm)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  stat_smooth(geom='line', alpha=0.5, se=FALSE, size=1, col='red') + 
  labs(title = 'Total cyclists per day across Auckland counters from 2016-2018 with rainfall', x='Date', y='Total', col='Rainfall (mm)' ))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

(plot2 <- final_tidy %>% ggplot(aes(x=DayOfYear, y=total, group=factor(year(date)), col=factor(year(date)))) + 
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) + 
  geom_smooth() + 
  labs(title='Total cyclists per day across Auckland counters', x='Day of year', y='Total', col='Year') + 
  theme_classic())
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

plot3 <- final_tidy %>% ggplot(aes(x=DayOfYear, y=total, col=mean_rain_mm)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_grid(year(date)~season, scale='free') +
  labs(title='Total cyclists per day across Auckland counters by season and year', x='Day of year', y='Total', col='Rainfall (mm)')
  

plot3_ <- ggplot_gtable(ggplot_build(plot3))
plot3_$widths[11] <- 4*plot3_$widths[11] #adjust summer width for easier comparison 
grid::grid.draw(plot3_)

(plot4 <- final_tidy %>% ggplot(aes(x=wday, y=total)) +
  geom_boxplot()) +
  facet_grid(year(date)~season) +
  labs(title='Total cyclists across Auckland counters by season, weekday and year', x='Weekday', y='Total')

Simple regression model for predicting number of cyclists from year, season, day of the week, and rain.

bike.fit <- lm(total~season*mean_rain_mm*year*wday, data=final_tidy)
anova(bike.fit)

Does rain have a big impact on the number of people cycling in Auckland?

Yes, the graphs suggest there are lower numbers of cyclists across Auckland when there is higher rainfall in Auckland. This is confirmed from the regression model which shows that for each mm of rainfall the number of cyclists decreases by about 5000 to 5700. This is a significant proportion of the average number of cyclists counted per weekday and across seasons and years therefore its impact is of great practical significance.
